Framing ADHD in this way was really helpful to me personally. Nearly everyone knows what it's like to deal with tech issues; the same feeling of frustration translates.

ccing @carrhamey @danidonovan @ErynnBrook and the rest of #adhdtwitter in case the above 🧵 is helpful

It's not your fault that the program crashes, by the way. It's just software that is slightly incompatible with your own hardware. 

So you find patches for the program. Or learn to save often. Sometimes you have to re-create work when the program crashes and you forgot to save.
Sometimes the program loads okay, and then you think "great, I fixed the bug, now I'm going to enjoy this program forever!" ... but then the program eventually crashes again, because it ALWAYS does.

Neurotypical people just click the mouse, the program opens, and off they go.

But for people with neurodiversity and executive function issues, sometimes the mouse doesn't work. The program will often freeze or crash. Sometimes you have to restart the system.

Of course I can't remember where I read this now, but I heard a brilliant analogy for #ADHD the other day. 

Having ADHD is like trying to run a computer program, but there is a glitch in the program where it seldom loads correctly. 

For people without ADHD, they can just start.

Ultimately, I see a deeper schizm coming for our larger society; it will benefit nobody but the ultra-rich who won't be effected by it. Call it a Cassandra-esque prophesy, I guess. I don't want to see this happen but I fear it will.

We need to be better to each other NOW.

12/12

Also, if I may be so blunt, if we had a government who had previously shown that they take care of people at all levels of society, we wouldn't have nearly this level of mistrust either. That's another piece that needs to be addressed.

11/

By "better care" I mean personally having some goddamn empathy for other individuals. As well, we need much better social supports put in place at a federal/global level. 

Covid is causing disabilities and right now our world is not kind to those who are disabled.

10/

I guess what I'm saying here is that the only way we're going to get out of this pandemic without a goddamn civil war or an extinction-level event is if we start taking better care of each other instead of dividing ourselves further. 

9/

Also, let's consider that while unvaccinated people are the ones more likely to get the new strain of the virus... people who have been vaxxed are part of the problem in spreading it too, especially the ones who no longer feel the need to wear masks.

8/

If you're telling someone that they're a horrible person and that you're going to shun them if they don't comply... you're also sending out the message that you yourself are not trustworthy or safe to be around for that person. No matter your intent behind the words. 

7/

As well, it's worrisome when people who were previously rational, empathetic adults revert to groupthink and "us vs them" between vaxxed and not vaxxed. 

Yes, people are caught up in fear, but some have taken it to an almost cult-like mentality, seemingly devoid of empathy. 

6/

The government needs to do more to provide adequate support to individuals in these unfortunate positions. 

If there were more transparent, honest conversations and more accountability and support from the healthcare system, there'd be more trust.

5/

What we've been seeing is that people who suffer from long-haul Covid and/or from side effects to the vaccine are being minimized and swept under the rug, or treated like acceptable casualities for "the greater good".  

No wonder individuals are scared.

4/

Income inequality, lack of affordable housing, lack of comprehensive healthcare, lack of social supports, racial injustice, police abuse of power... these are just some of the many inequities that the pandemic has brought to the surface of the collective consciousness.

3/

We need to acknowledge that there is no true "normal" from the before times that is worth going back to, especially for the people who were already struggling pre-pandemic. 

People are tired of being treated as disposable. 

2/

Maybe-controversial opinion, but... if you want people to move past vaccine hestiancy and get vaccinated, you need to actively demonstrate that you care about the people themselves... and not just their social compliance so that things can "get back to normal."

1/
